            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#JP">
                <p>Publius Stertinius Threptus paved the Platea Aelia with his own money</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>Silvestrini proposes that the name of the platea (a wide street, not a square, and so very probably
                    the decumanus maximus) should be linked to the visit of the Emperor Hadrian in 125 AD. Naming of
                    streets after an emperor in this fashion finds parallels. Other instances of platea inscriptions are
                    known in Sicily (AE 1964.181 and AE 1964.182 both from Marsala; and AE 1997.740 from Segesta). The
                    name implies a freedman (Silvestrini notes the significant family of Stertinii from the early C2 AD,
                    and that perhaps they have a Sicilian origin on the basis of this text; at 223 n.63 Silvestrini
                    speculates a link with the recently found Isis dedication from Lilybaeum (noted in Silvestrini
                    (2011) 464 n.6), by a Rufinius, which could be cos. of 162, D. Fonteius Frontinianus L. Stertinius
                    Rufinus.
                </p>
            </div>
